                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d309">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">862.1281/85: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Germany</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gilbert</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-08-03T17:00:00+01:00"
                            >August 3, 1938—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received August 3—3:20 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>372. The D. N. B.<note n="46" xml:id="d309fn46">Deutsches Nachrichten
                        Büro.</note> reports the enactment of an ordinance (not yet Promulgated)
                    canceling as of September 30 of this year the licenses <pb facs="0396" n="388"
                        xml:id="pg_388"/> to practice of all Jewish physicians. It is not yet clear
                    how this affects their possible practice among other Jews<note n="47"
                        xml:id="d309fn47">From the text of law promulgated on August 4, it appeared
                        that a limited number of Jewish physicians would be permitted to practice
                        among Jewish patients.</note> or foreigners.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gilbert</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
